Project: Investigation of the data of about 10,000 movies collected from The Movie Database (TMDb)¶

Introduction¶

This data set contains information about 10,000 movies collected from The Movie Database (TMDb)¶

Questions¶

  1. Which genres are most popular from year to year?
  2. What is the ditribution of the quantitative variables?
  3. What kinds of properties are associated with movies that have high revenues?
  4. With which particular keywords and genres did movies generate higher popularity ratings, average votes, revenues and return on investment?
  5. Which directors and actors are most successful on average with all their films according to movies' popularity, return on investment and average vote?
  6. Does the budget of a movie really play a role in its profitability?

Research Question 1 (Which genres are most popular from year to year?)¶

In our data the column 'genres' has some missing values. So we'll drop the rows with these missing values:

In [8]:
df_genres = df.dropna(subset=['genres'])
df_genres.reset_index(drop=True, inplace=True)
df_genres['genres'].isnull().sum()
Out[8]:
0

And the column 'genres' contain multiple values separated by pipe (|) characters. Let's fix this and create a new dataframe without (|) at least in the column 'genres'

In [9]:
# 'genres' columns with (|):
genres_with_pipe = df_genres[df_genres['genres'].str.contains('|')]
genres_with_pipe.shape[0] == df_genres.shape[0]
Out[9]:
True

It has turned out that all cells in the column 'genres' contain (|)

If we know that how many pipes every cell in the "genres" column contains, we can split and create a new dataframe with replication (times number of pipes + 1) of every row with a single genre name in each

In [10]:
df_genres['genres'].str.count('|')

Oops, this is not what I want, so I will fix this like the following

In [12]:
df_genres.loc[:,'genres'] = df_genres['genres'].str.replace("|", ";")
pipe_count = df_genres['genres'].str.count(';')
pipe_count
Out[12]:
0        3
1        3
2        2
3        3
4        2
        ..

10840    1

And we will generate a new dataframe

In [ ]:
df_new = pd.concat([df_genres.iloc[0:1, :]]*((pipe_count+1)[0]), ignore_index=True)
df_new['genres'] = df_new.loc[0, 'genres'].split(';')
for n in range(1, df_genres.shape[0]):
    t = pd.concat([df_genres.iloc[n:(n+1), :]]*((pipe_count+1)[n]), ignore_index=True)
    t['genres'] = t.loc[0, 'genres'].split(';')
    df_new = df_new.append(t, ignore_index=True)
df_new

I took about 5 minutes for the above algorithm to finish. Sa I came up with a better solution:

In [32]:
dfnew = pd.DataFrame(np.repeat(df_genres.values, list(pipe_count+1), axis=0))
dfnew.columns = df_genres.columns
dfnew['genres'] = list(np.concatenate(df_genres['genres'].str.split(';')))
dfnew.shape

(26960, 21)

Research Question 2 (What is the ditribution of the quantitative variables?)¶

The only variables that can be relevant in this question are the columns "popularity", "budget_mln", "revenue_mln", "runtime", "vote_average", "budget_adj_mln" and "revenue_adj_mln". So let's draw histograms for these parameters

In [20]:
qt_df= df[['popularity', 'budget_mln', 'revenue_mln', 'runtime', 'vote_average', 'budget_adj_mln', 'revenue_adj_mln']]
columns = qt_df.columns
columns
for n in columns:
    qt_df[[n]].hist()

As we look at the histograms, we can see that low popular movies and zero-budget or low-budget movies comprises far most of the dataset. Runtime of most of the films fall between 100 and 180 minutes. The distribution of vote-average is centered around 6 and quite normal.

Research Question 4 (With which particular keywords and genres did movies generate higher popularity ratings, average votes, revenues and return on investment?)¶

For genres¶

For 'genres' let's return to the dataframe 'dfnew'. For popularity ratings there is no need to drop the outliers as we have seen from the disciption of the data that they are relatively scarce. So we will turn to 'dfnew' and create a bar chart for show average popularity of every genre. But first and foremost let's creat bar_chart function.

In [23]:
def bar_chart(x,y, x_label, y_label, title):
    x_labels = x
    y_labels = y
    plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))
    plt.bar(x_labels, y_labels, width=0.6)
    plt.ylabel(y_label, fontweight='bold')
    plt.xlabel(x_label, fontweight='bold')
    plt.xticks(range(len(x_labels)), x_labels, rotation=75)
    plt.title(title, fontweight='bold')
In [65]:
dfnew[['popularity']] = dfnew.loc[:, ['popularity']].apply(pd.to_numeric)
x = dfnew[['genres', 'popularity']].groupby('genres').mean()['popularity'].sort_values(ascending=False).index
y = dfnew[['genres', 'popularity']].groupby('genres').mean()['popularity'].sort_values(ascending=False)

For return on investment we should calculate (revenue_adj_mln - budget_adj_mln)/budget_adj_mln. If budget_adj_mln = 0, we receive an error message. So let's drop zero values in both 'budget_adj_mln' and 'revenue_adj_mln' in order to avoid distortion, and create 'return_on_inv' column

In [71]:
dfnew_non_zero = dfnew[(dfnew['budget_adj_mln'] != 0) & (dfnew['revenue_adj_mln'] != 0)]
dfnew_non_zero['return_on_inv'] = (dfnew_non_zero['revenue_adj_mln'] - dfnew_non_zero['budget_adj_mln'])*100/dfnew_non_zero['budget_adj_mln']

Conclusions¶

For question 1.¶

"Adventure", "animation" and "fantasy" movies have been most popular throughout the years.

For question 2.¶

Low popular movies and zero-budget or low-budget movies comprises far most of the dataset. Runtime of most of the films fall between 100 and 180 minutes. The distribution of vote-average is centered around 6 and quite normal.

For question 3.¶

Movies that have higher revenues have higher budgets, popularity, average votes and runtime than movies that have lower revenues.

For question 4.¶

For genres:

  • "Adventure", "Science Fiction", "Fantasy" and "Action" are top 4 genres in terms of average popularity ratings of movies.
  • ""Documentary", "Music", "History" and "Animation" are top 4 genres in terms of average votes of movies.
  • "Animation", "Adventure", "Fantasy" and "Family" are top 4 genres in terms of average revenues (inflation adjusted) of movies.
  • "Family", "Romance", "Adventure" and "Action" are top 4 genres in terms of average ROI (return on investment) of movies.
For keywords:
  • "Velociraptor", "nihilism", "woman with gun" and "scene during end credits" are top 4 keywords of films in terms of their average popularity.
  • "Hindi cinema", "nouvelle vague", "cinema nove" and "russian cinema" are top 4 keywords in terms of movies' vote_average.
  • "Space war", "hermit", "lightsaber" and "iceberg" are top 4 keywords in terms of average revenues of films.
  • "Okinawa", "revanche" and "self esteem" are top vivid keywords in terms of movies' average return on investment.

For question 5.¶

For directors:

  • Colin Trevorrow, David Leitch, Chad Stahelski and are top 3 successful film directors in terms of average popularity of their movies.
  • All the top 10 directors with highest vote_average had almost the same vote_average with each other, except for Mark Cousins having slightly more.
  • Irwin Winkler, Clyde Geronimi, Hamilton Luske, Richard Marquand and Jennifer Lee are top 5 most successful directors in terms of their movies' revenues.
  • John G.Avildsen is paricularly the most successful director in terms of average return on investment for their movies.
For actors:
  • Josh Helman, Daisy Ridley, Hugh Keays-Byrne, and Ryan Potter are top 4 actors in terms of average popularity of movies they cast.
  • All the top 10 actors with highest vote_average had almost the same vote_average with each other.
  • Jason Miller, Daisy Ridley and Robert MacNaughton are top 3 actors in terms of average revenues of movies they cast.
  • Charlie Tanimoto, Yuji Okumoto and Martin Kove are top 3 actors in terms of average return of investment on movies they cast.

For question 6.¶

The correlation is 0.47 and weak between films' budgets and profits, so spending too much money does not always promise high profits in the film industry.
